.chap(Writing Programs in PPL,programs)

All examples of PPL commands up to now have been
in the form of !<direct statements>, that is,
statements typed in by the user for immediate
execution.  Although PPL allows single statements
of considerable complexity, through the use of ~FOR~, ~IF~, ~WHILE~, and ~REPEAT~
.x FOR form
.x IF form
.x WHILE form
.x REPEAT form
forms, this mode of operation is really
useful only for desk-calculator type computations.

We now consider the writing of !<programs>.  A <<program>
is simply a sequence of PPL statements typed in by the user
and stored to await later execution.
Subsequently,
we can command PPL to execute these statements.

.sec(User-Defined Functions,functiondef)

PPL allows the user to define his own
functions in such a way that they may be called
in exactly the same manner as the built-in
functions described in {"Section!" functioncalls~.
Function definition is the means by which a set
.x function definition
.x definition,function
of PPL statements may be stored for later execution.

A user-defined function consists of a
!<function header> and a set of numbered statements
.x function header
.x header,function
comprising the !<body> (executable part) of the function.
.x function body
.x body,function
As these statements are typed in, PPL stores
them away rather than executing them immediately.

The following example will be used
to explain the mechanics of function definition.
The defined function, called ~<<FACT>~, takes a single
~INT~eger argument !<n> and computes !<n> <<factorial>.
!<n> factorial (abbreviated !<n>! in mathematics)
is simply the product of all the positive integers
less than or equal to !<n>.
This, of course, is a simple thing to do in 
direct PPL statements; for example, we could compute
ten factorial as follows:

.examp
\TENFAC_1
\FOR I_1:10 DO TENFAC_TENFAC*I
\TENFAC
3628800
.end

However, if we then wanted to compute the factorial
of each of a large set of different integers,
we would have
to repeat the above statements each time.
What we really want to do is define the function
~FACT~ in such a way that calling it will deliver
the desired results; for example:

.examp
\FACT(10)
3628800
.end

This may be done through the following !<function
definition>:

.examp
\$FACT(N); I
   [1]\FACT_1.0
   [2]\FOR I_1:N DO FACT_FACT*I
   [3]\$
.end

The first line of the definition begins
with a @@<dollar sign,signalling function definition>.  This is a signal to PPL that
what is being typed is a definition rather than
an executable statement.
After the dollar sign is the name of the @/<function,name/of>
(~FACT~), which may be any legal identifier
that has not previously been defined.
Within the body of the function, this name
(referred to as the !<procedure identifier>)
is used as a simple variable which represents
the value of the function; during execution,
the last value assigned
.xx procedure identifier,assignment,to
to the %<procedure/identifier> (by
a statement of the form 3FACT#_#2e1)
will be the value of the function call (e.g. 3FACT(10)1#).

Following the procedure identifier appears
the !<dummy argument list> enclosed in @@<parentheses,enclosing dummy arguments>.
Each %<dummy/argument> is an identifier.  If more than
one dummy argument is listed, the arguments are
separated by @@<comma,separating dummy arguments>s.  If the function takes no
arguments, the parentheses are omitted.  Dummy
arguments are used within the body of the function
to refer to the
values of the corresponding arguments specified
when the function is called.

The last part of the function header
is a list of !<local variable names>.  These are separated
.x local variable
.x variable,local
from the rest of the header by a @@<semicolon,preceding local variables>;  if
more than one local exist they are separated by @@<comma,separating local variables>s or semicolons.
These variables are called !<local> because their
names are accessible only within the body of
the function in which they are defined.  Thus, within
the sample function ~FACT~, the variable ~I~
is a local.  It is entirely separate from any meaning
the identifier ~I~ may have either within other functions
or in the %<global/environment> (in which control
resides when PPL is started).  The use
of locals is an effective means of avoiding name
conflicts between identically-named variables
in different functions.

The dummy arguments (sometimes known
as !<formal parameters>) may also be treated as locals,
.see formal parameter,dummy argument
.see parameter,argument
in the sense that they are accessible only
within the function that uses them.  Formal parameters
and locals differ in one respect, however.  Whereas
formals are initialized with the &/<value/of/dummy argument>s of the
calling arguments when the user function is entered,
locals initially have no &/<value/of/local variable>.  This is true
on each function entry no matter how many times
the same function is called.  The @/<procedure identifier,value/of> is likewise unassigned on entry.

The function header line is terminated normally,
by pressing the <<Return key>.  PPL now responds
by typing 3[1]1, indicating that it is prepared
to accept the first statement of the function.
PPL statements may be typed in this manner on
successive lines, with the %<line/number>s supplied
automatically by PPL.
In this case, we type in the two statements required
to compute !<n> factorial, much as we typed in direct
statements to compute ten factorial, except that PPL
does not !<execute> these statements but rather !<stores>
them away for later execution.
(We have made one minor modification to the algorithm:
namely, we initialize ~FACT~ to the ~<<REAL>~ value 1.0 rather
than to the ~<<INT>~eger value 1; this is because
factorials can be very large, and a ~REAL~ is capable
of storing much larger numbers than an ~INT~.
Further information about PPL's handling
of numbers will be presented in {"Section!" morenumbers~.)

The @<function definition,closing> is !<closed> by typing in
a line containing only a @/<dollar sign,closing function/with>.  This indicates the
end of the definition, and PPL responds by
skipping a line and moving
eight spaces from the left margin.

Now that the &<function/call> has been defined, it
may be called:

.examp
\FACT(3)
6.
\FACT(10)
3.6288E+06
\25+FACT(FACT(4))
6.204484E+23
.end

In the first example above, the call of
the function ~FACT~ takes place as follows.
The argument (3) is evaluated and assigned as
the value of the formal parameter ~N~ within
.xx dummy argument,assignment,to
the function being called.  Control is then passed
to statement [1] of ~FACT~.

Unless otherwise directed, PPL executes
.xx function,execution order,of
statements within the function in numerical
order.  Thus, statements [1] and [2] are
executed.  Upon finishing statement [2], PPL
attempts to execute statement [3], which does not
exist (note that statement [3] is !<not> a line
containing a dollar sign;  the dollar sign was simply
a command to close the function definition).
By convention, execution of a user-defined
function is terminated whenever an attempt is
made to execute a nonexistent statement.

When a function terminates or !<returns>,
.xx function,return,from
the currently-assigned value of the procedure
identifier (~FACT~) is taken as the value
of the function and substituted in the
.xx function call,value,of
calling expression.  If the procedure identifier
was never assigned a value during the execution
of the @<function,null-value-returning>, the value returned is a special constant
called ~NULL~ (which does not print out under ordinary circumstances).

.sec(GOTO and RETURN,gotos)

To allow the programmer to modify the sequence in which
statements in a function are executed, PPL provides two
program control statements called ~<<GOTO>~ and ~<<RETURN>~.
The ~GOTO~ statement, which is written in the form

.examp
\GOTO %!<n>
.end

where !<n> is an integer statement number,
causes PPL immediately to transfer control and resume execution
starting at statement [!<n>].

The ~RETURN~ statement causes the function to terminate immediately,
as if the last statement of the function had just been executed.
The word ~RETURN~ may optionally be followed by an expression, i.e.
in the form

.examp
\RETURN !<e>
.end

in which case the value of the expression !<e> is assigned to the
procedure identifier before the function returns (making it be
the value of the @/<function call,value/of>).

As an example of the use of both ~GOTO~ and ~RETURN~, we shall define
a procedure called ~<<EUCLID>~ which takes two positive ~INT~eger
arguments and computes their %<greatest common/divisor> (gcd) using
.see gcd,greatest common divisor
Euclid's algorithm:

.examp
\$EUCLID(M,N); R
   [1]\R _ M-N*IDIV(M,N)
   [2]\IF R=0 THEN RETURN N
   [3]\M_N; N_R; GOTO %1
   [4]\$

\EUCLID(10,25)
5
\EUCLID(29,37)
1
\EUCLID(544,119)
17
.end

In statement [1], we compute the remainder from dividing ~M~ by ~N~
(using the built-in function {fn(IDIV,a,b)~, described in
{"Section!" conversion~, which always gives an ~INT~eger
result if the arguments are both of type ~INT~).
In statement [2], if this remainder is zero,
then ~N~ is the desired greatest common divisor, so we return it
as the value of the function.  Otherwise, we continue to statement [3],
where we perform assignments to convert the problem into that of
finding the gcd of ~N~ and ~R~ and then go back to statement [1].

Note that the referenced line number is preceded by a @@<percent sign,introducing relocatable line number>.
This means 'relocatable line 1', and, as we shall see, comes in very
.x relocatable line number
.x line number,relocatable
handy if we later have to edit the function (discussed in
{"Section!" textedit~).  However, statement [3] could just as well
have been written as

.examp
   [3]\M_N; N_R; GOTO 1
.end

except that the number '1' would no longer be relocatable
(i.e. subject to automatic correction by PPL when statements
of the function are renumbered).  It is a good idea, therefore,
to get into the habit of using a percent sign before all line
number references.

.sec(FOR Statements,forstmt)

Besides the ~FOR~ !<form> already discussed,
.x FOR form
whose scope is at most the rest of the statement, PPL
also provides the ~FOR~ !<statement>, whose &/<scope/of/FOR statement>
.x FOR statement
may extend over one or more other statements in a function.
The ~FOR~ statement is written in the following format:

.examp
   [!<k>]\FOR !<v> _ !<i> : !<s> : !<f> <<DOTHRU> %!<n>
 [!<k>+1]\       . . . .
\        . . . .
   [!<n>]\         . . . .
.end

Whenever a ~FOR~ statement is encountered during execution,
it causes the statements !<k>+1 through !<n> to be executed
repeatedly for each successive value of the controlled variable !<v>.

There are a few rules that must be followed when using the ~FOR~
statement.  First, it must stand alone on a single line; i.e.
the statement

.examp
\IF X=3 THEN FOR I_1:10 DOTHRU %7
.end

is illegal (though, as usual, the quantities
!<v>, !<i>, !<s>, !<f>, and !<n> may be arbitrary expressions).
Second, by its very nature, the ~FOR~ statement
is legal only as a statement of a function; i.e.
it must be a !<stored> statement, and may not be typed in
for immediate execution.  Finally, the scope of the ~FOR~
statement must be non-empty; that is, !<n> must be greater
than !<k>.

Just to illustrate the use of the ~FOR~ statement,
we shall define another factorial function called ~<<FACT2>~,
which differs from ~FACT~ ({"Section!" functiondef~) only in that the iteration
is spread over two statements by the use of a ~FOR~ statement.

.examp
\$FACT2(N); I
   [1]\FACT2_1.0
   [2]\FOR I_1:N DOTHRU %3
   [3]\FACT2_FACT2*I
   [4]\$

\FACT2(12)
4.790016E+08
.end

.sec(Nesting and Recursion,recursion)

Since any statement that may be submitted for
direct execution is also legal as a step of a function,
it follows that functions may call other functions
in the manner already considered.
This is known as !<nested> @/<function call,nesting/of>ing,
and it may be carried on to any reasonable depth.

In PPL, it is perfectly legal
for a function to call itself.  This technique
is known as !<recursion> and is 
.x recursion
useful in many applications.
In writing recursive functions, it should
be borne in mind that @@<local variable,behavior in recursive call>s
belonging to nested calls of the
same function are completely independent.
Locals within the called function are
not visible to the caller or vice versa.

Recursion is used extensively in many higher-level computer
applications (for example, the syntax recognizer in PPL is
recursive); however, a simple example should suffice to demonstrate
the general principle.  We shall define a recursive
<<factorial> function in terms of itself, as follows:

.examp
\$<<RFACT>(N)
   [1]\IF N<1 THEN RFACT_1.0 ELSE RFACT_N*RFACT(N-1)
   [2]\$

\RFACT(19)
1.216451E+17
.end

This function computes the factorial by using the
knowledge that

.begin nofill tabs 9

\!<n>! = !<n>*(!<n>-1)!
.end

where 0! is defined as one.  Thus, in computing 3RFACT(19)1,
the ~RFACT~ function is actually called (recursively) 19 times.
Each successive call is nested within a single expression
in statement [1] of the caller.  When the calls reach a depth
of 19, the value of the dummy argument ~N~ at the deepest
level is zero, and thus 1.0 is returned as the value of the
call at this level.  It should be emphasized once again
that the values of the procedure identifier ~RFACT~
and of the parameter ~N~ are completely independent
at each level.

A final note: if a parameterless procedure
.xx parameterless procedure,recursive call,of
calls itself recursively, the call must be made by appending
an empty pair of parentheses to the name.
Otherwise, PPL will assume that what is
wanted is the current value of the procedure
identifier rather than the value obtained by calling the
function again.

.sec(Labels,labels)

PPL has a provision for <<label>ling statements with
names as well as numbers.  A !<label> is an
@@<identifier,label> immediately followed by a @@<colon,delimiting label> at the
beginning of a stored statement (i.e. a step of
a user-defined function).
Defining a label in this way causes the identifier
to be declared a local variable and initialized with
the number of the containing statement.
For example, the following function will
operate identically to the one defined in {"Section!" gotos~:

.examp
\$<<EUCLID>(M,N); R
   [1]\COMPUTE.REMAINDER:  R _ M-N*IDIV(M,N)
   [2]\IF R=0 THEN RETURN N
   [3]\M_N; N_R; GOTO COMPUTE.REMAINDER
   [4]\$
.end

Labels are particularly handy when you are composing a
function at the terminal and you need to refer (in a ~GOTO~ or
~FOR~ statement) to a statement later in the function which you
haven't defined yet.

.sec(Comments,comments)
.x comment

In a program that is at all complicated,
it is a good idea to add explanitory material in the
form of !<comments>.  Liberal use
of comments aids programming in several ways,
not the least of which is making the operation
of the program clearer to the user and to other programmers.
In PPL, a comment may be appended to any statement
by preceding it with a string of three @@<period,denoting comment>s.
When PPL sees three periods it considers the
rest of the line to be a comment and
ignores it.  However, if the statement
is stored as part of a user-defined function,
the comment remains in the text and is printed
out when the function is displayed using
the question-mark command (introduced in {"Section!" textedit~).
The user is warned that the first period should not
be adjacent to a digit;  otherwise, the period
may be construed as a decimal point and the comment
as part of the statement.  A separation of a single
space or Tab is sufficient.

.sec(Continuation,continuation)
.xx statement,continuation,of

Where necessary, a statement may be continued on
more than one line.  To continue to a new line, the
<<percent-sign> character (%) is used at the end of the line.*<In PDP-10 PPL
versions prior to 53, line continuation is accomplished by
pressing the Line-Feed (LF) key.>
PPL spaces down one line,
moves eight spaces from the left margin, but
does not print a statement number.  There are only two
restrictions on the use of continuation lines:
first, a single !<lexeme> (@@<number,lexeme>, @@<identifier,lexeme>, multi-character
.x lexeme
@@<operator,lexeme>, etc.) may not be split between lines.
Second, the entire statement may not be more than
500 characters in length.
.x length of statement
Continuing a statement
within a ~STRING~ causes a Return and a Line-Feed
.x Return key
.xx STRING,continuation,within
(or the single Newline character in the PDP-11 version)
to be included within the ~STRING~:

.examp tabs 9,35
\"THIS IS A%\7Percent sign for continuation.3
\SPLIT STRING"
THIS IS A
SPLIT STRING
.end

For convenience, there is a variable in PPL called ~<<NEWLINE>~,
predefined to contain a ~STRING~ consisting of the special
characters above in precisely this manner (i.e. as if the
statement

.examp
\NEWLINE _ "%
\"
.end

had been executed).  This is useful as an argument to the
~PRINT~ function when it is desired to advance to the next line.
.x line advance
